Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word using standard library functions:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map> // Using map for storing lines as an alternative to getting out of memory issue with large files

std::string keyword = "word_to_search"; // Set your keyword here
std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt"); // Replace "input.txt" with your file path
std::string line;
size_t count = 0;
std::map<int, std::string> lines; // Store lines instead of reading into small buffer to avoid memory issues

if (inputFile.is_open()) {
    int lineNumber = 1;
    while (getline(inputFile, line)) {
        lines[lineNumber++] = line; // Store each line in a map
        size_t pos = line.find(keyword); // Find position of keyword in current line
        if (pos!= std::string::npos) { // If keyword is found
            ++count;
        }
    }
} else {
    std::cout << "Unable to open file\n";
}

inputFile.close();

std::cout << "\nTotal Occurrences of \"" << keyword << "\": " << count << "\n";
// To display all lines and their respective keywords positions use below code snippet uncommenting it
/*for (const auto& entry : lines){
    std::cout<<"Line Number:"<<entry.first<<"\tLine Content:"<<entry.second<<"\n";
}*/
```

Replace `"input.txt"` with the actual file name or path, and replace `"word_to_search"` with the desired keyword. This program uses a `std::map` to store entire lines read from the file which can handle larger files without running out of memory.

To implement a Queue data structure using two Stacks in Python, we'll follow the common approach where Stack1 and Stack2 will represent the "in" (input or enqueue) part and "out" (output or dequeue) part of the queue respectively. Here is an implementation:

```python
class Stack:
    def __init__(self):
        self.items = []

class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.inStack = Stack() # Input stack
        self.outStack = Stack() # Output stack

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.inStack.push(item) # Add to input stack

    def dequeue(self):
    # If output stack is empty first then move all elements from input stack to output stack
    if len(self.outStack) == 0:
        while len(self.inStack)>0:
            self.outStack.push(self.inStack.pop())

    # Now return the top element from output stack
    return self.outStack.pop()

# Testing the code
q = Queue()
q.enqueue("A")
q.enqueue("B")
print(q.dequeue()) # A
q.enqueue("C")
print(q.dequeue()) # B
print(q.dequeue()) # C
```

In this example, `Queue` class has two properties - an instance of Stack named as 'inStack' for adding items (enqueue), and another one called 'outStack' which is used for removing items (dequeue). The method `enqueue` simply adds an item into the input stack. In order to perform dequeue operation, it checks whether there are any items present in the output stack or not; if not, it moves all the items from the input stack to the output stack before returning the head item from the output stack.
